review_blob: Chocolate head with tar body. Literally a porter with more booze and lots of dry hopping. This may sound like a slam on the Gonz, but make no mistake, this brew is a tasy one. Sticky with malt and super hoppy but nice n bready as a porter should be. If I come across the barrel aged twin Ill double the dose for sure.

Particularly nice DPA. The aroma is very fragrant heavy fruity/floral scent and just enough malt, with licorice and resiny pine.  Flavor is best described as the lovechild of a strong IPA and a fruity belgian trippel. Wonderful taste of figs, raisins, pine, citrus, licorice, white grapes and hot malt the palate both chalky and oily at the same time. The real winner here is the warm, boozy - in a good way - finish, with the ten-five staying hidden until the bitter end. Warms like a dry white wine. Better than I expected... Ill buy again for sure.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: Reminiscent of Bells Expedition Stout but slightly less caramel and alot more hops. The hop profile of the Oak Aged Yeti sets it apart from the other imperials out there. Also not as sticky as the Expedition. I hate licorice but was looking for it here and didnt find it. Sweet tongue and doughy bready body. The long dirty finish is warm and superboozy with smoky vanilla and just a little bit of spice from the oak. I shouldve had the Yeti first but I will most certainly try it now to see how the character stacks up to the oak version. I do like how it threw me off not having notes of dark fruit or licorice to go with the usual chocolate and coffee the way other imperial stouts do. Top five easy.
beer_name: Great Divide Yeti Imperial Stout - Oak Aged

review_blob: Bottle: Aroma is dark berries and fruits and supermalt. Pours the inkiest, blackest, holy shit-est dark black in the glass with dark brown head. Head dissipates quick but covers the top all the way down. First flavors I got were salty and sweet coffee, followed by boozy licorice and spicy chocolate. As the drink warmed I picked up grapes, figs, earth, grass, caramel, and prunes. So thick, so sweet and chewy! My lips got so sticky when I drank this midnight oil that I thought I was weezing the juice straight from a spigot on a Michigan maple; all the while my tongue was covered in buttery goodness.  Sorry, Celebrator! Found a new number one. Bravo to the boys of K-zoo on the Megastout. Holy shit.

CO2 draught: Murky dark brown, off-white lace. No nose! Flavor is coffee and grocery store brand chocolate ice cream. Dry and delicious. More hops than some other stouts Ive had, and the CO2 was a little rough. No problem finding the bitter chalky finish that I was looking for. Overall this one was original enough have another soon.

Alot like the Optimator, but way more fragrant. Aroma of honey, fig, and caramelly malt. I think I smelled a little sandalwood in there somewhere. Rich, sweet malty flavor of caramel, figs, grain, toast and cola. Softer CO2 would have for a better palate. Finish is a little less dirty than I had hoped for, but overall this is a solid doppel.

Draught: Beautiful creamy head atop a smoky peach color. Unbelievable aroma! Peaches and pine and maybe a little orange citrus. Very floral as well. Flavor is fruity orange but not oversweet. Nice oily texture coats the entire mouth. Peachy finish stretches out and does not want to let go. Wonderful double.

Draught: Sour, grainy nose. Not much head or lace. Tastes like a fruity Shiner Bock. Other flavors include figs, caramel, maple syrup and dark bread. Long, tangy finish with a little bitterness. Hoppier than the Celebrator or Salvator. What I found very interesting is the spicy cinnamon flavor that came out after taking a bite of a delicious sandwich that had horseradish on it. Decent.

Aroma is orange blossom and treated lumber.Foggy orange-amber color with lots of fine particles. The big foamy head left wet lace in the glass but it all dissipates rather quickly. Fruity orange and peach flavor. Wet palate and superdry chalky bitter finish.

Amber, one finger head. Smells like malt, malt, malt. Flavor is sweet, spicy and slightly bitter. The palate is what wins it here; CO2 is at the perfect level, letting the roasted pine oil up the roof of the mouth.The rich, roasted malt character of the finish was my favorite part of the 90 minute.
UPDATED: MAY 24, 2008

Pours dark mahogany with a foamy tan head that will do the deed to the bottom, leaving lovely lace in the glass. A knockout of an aroma: candied figs and prunes, toffee, pumpernickel bread, white grapes and earth. First sip gave flavor of dark chocolate covered espresso beans. Everything after that was all over the place! Dark belgian chocolate, Antiguan coffee, caramel, molasses and butterscotch ala Werthers original. This is the crazy part: my grandma has always had these little strawberry hard candies at Christmas that have strawberry goo in the center. They are wrapped in a cellophane and foil wrapper that looks like a strawberry on the outside. If you were to cook these candies in a pot on the stove and ever so slightly burn the syrup, the resulting flavor and aroma would be what I picked up in this beer. Whew! Every time I take a drink I enjoy the FINISH more than the initial flavors. This finish is second in length only to, from what I have experienced, the North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout, but the first place trophy overall goes to the Celebrator. The finish is long and dirty with loads of flavor and not too chalky or bitter like one would expect. The next time I am in good company after a large meal i.e. Thanksgiving, I will make sure I have enough Celebrator on hand for everyone to raise a glass.
UPDATED: JUN 28, 2008

12oz bottle: Looks good in the glass, dark yellow with a foamy head and laces like seafoam all the way. I have to agree with most here when it comes to the aroma, there really isnt much to speak of. What aroma there is, oddly enough, is less hoppy than the Sam Adams Boston Lager. There is a rush of sweetness and some slight bitterness on the sides of the tongue but that completely disappears in a hurry. Watery mouthfeel and literally no finish.

Beautiful dark copper with an off white creamy head and decent lacing. Reminds me of Yuengling Lager. Somewhat metallic. Roasted, grainy watery palate and a touch of hop. Better from the tap  than the can.

Pale gold with just about no white head on draught, none at all in the bottle. Forget about lace, this brew goes buck naked. Grainy aroma, flavor is built of bubblegum, strawberries, yeast and cooked corn. Finished clean with a hint of biscuit. I give a "high" 2.2 on account of the [very mild] flavor complexity.

Buttered toast aroma with maple syrup. Shrunken head syndrome but still has lovely lacing on draught. Copper and cloudy. Sweet but not too sweet on the tongue, fizzy CO2 and watery palate give way to a clean finish. You should be able to get this beer just about anywhere. Solid 3.

On draught, Smithwicks wears lace well.  Clear medium brown color, aroma of sourdough toast and caramel. Sweet malty caramel and macadamia flavor. Finish is on the sweet side but clean and quick. A session brew; nothing too impressive.

Had this brew on draught at Raglan Road. Light citrus aroma. Beautiful maize haze, but only a tiny little collar of foamy suds circled the glass and stayed all the way to the bottom. Delicious bubblegum and banana flavors with a long banana-y finish. Soft carbonation gave it a lovely palate and made it easy to enjoy. When no one was looking I took a nibble of the orange slice they served on the side. It enhanced the experience, but there is a time and a place for fresh fruit. Ill be looking to enjoy this hefe again before the week is over.

I cant give it less than a 1, because I am guilty of consuming this beverage when I could drink it or drink nothing. This is budweiser, just less supermalt flavor. Same CO2 level: too much. Not necessarily recommended for the five people on earth who havent had it yet.
Sweet, malty, bubbly. Aroma and flavor leave much to be desired. Malt is all you get.

12 ounce bottle: Faint aroma of citrus and sourdough. I was surprised to see such a good looking product-dark golden and hazy. The head was 2 fingers, creamy and laced to the bottom. Sweet flavor of citrus, but a watery palate and almost no finish. The beer looks great but lacks character.

Light orange/amber with a lasting head from the bottle. Sweet, piney grapefruit in the nose, with ginger, licorice, and prunes dipped in honey. Flavor was delicate and sweet from front to back. Soft CO2 doesnt disturb the deliciously bitter hops in the finish. Solid and tasty.

From the bottle: Aroma of grain, moderate hops, grass, light cheese, mustard and rollerskate. Sounds uninviting but it was a wonderfully refreshing character for me to experience. Clear pale yellow with an average one finger white frothy head that fully diminished, rather quickly too. Flavor and finish both a little acetic and somwhat sweet; the body oily but lively carbonated. Left chalk in the gutters. It may be that this one was skunked or it may be the character of the beer; either way I cant knock it and I definitely havent had my last.

Aroma is mild, balancing between the hops and buttery maltiness. Nice hazy gold color with a frothy white head & fair lacing. I even saw some tiny particles in there. Lively carbonation from this bottle. Flavor is sweet grain finishing to gentle hop bitterness, leaving traces of chalk in the back corners of the mouth. Overall solid clean brew.
beer_name: Flying Dog Tire Bite Golden Ale

review_blob: Not much of an aroma, albeit malty with a standard gold pour. One finger white head, little bit of lacing. From here on out it is best described as an earthier, slightly more bitter Corona Extra.

Fairly hoppy aroma with hints of orange citrus and coriander. Poured yellowish- orange with a fat pinky head that laced only a little. Medium bittersweet floral flavor with a short but satisfying finish. Soft carb and wide availability round this one out to be quite a solid pale ale.
UPDATED: MAY 13, 2008

Every time I find myself in Key West I make it a point to stumble into Willie Ts for a drink. The wife insists on Key West Sunset Ale. When I think Key West, I usually dont picture such a dark, autumnal beer. Medium brown color with virtually no head, so forget about lacing. Not very hoppy. Flavors of pumpkin, butterscotch, citrus, nuts, and light malt. Rather complex, actually until the finish when they all run out in a hurry and leave your palate a little boozy. I can get sixers of this beer at Sweetbay here in Tampa anytime.
beer_name: Florida Beer Key West Sunset Ale

review_blob: Goldish-tan in color, little head to talk about. Aroma is corny/grainy with a little honey. Flavor is nutty, grainy butterscotch with a surprisingly clean finish. It was fun down in the Bahamas but I honestly have no plans of returning there anytime just yet. Although it is readily available here in Tampa I have no reason to spend money on it when there are so many other brews I have yet to try.
UPDATED: MAY 10, 2008

Nothing special about this lager, as it has just what the Traditional Lager has... just less of it. If you find yourself fancying the Traditional Lager from YL but you dont like how malty it is, this Light version should suffice. But, like I said, nothing special. Still better than alot of the USA lights.

First had the Porter during the brewery tour here in Tampa. Dark brown in color, creamy khaki head that does lace nicely to the bottom. Coffee and pretzel in the nose. Semisweet chocolate and bread are the filling flavors here although not too heavy. Roasted finish sits for reflection. A classic porter.

Pours a lovely golden color, with an acceptable one finger head. The aroma is sweet and hoppy. Not much more than heavy malt and honey flavors here to give way to a semiclean finish. Surprised to see not much lacing in the glass.

Pours very pale golden from the bottle to the glass, with a small head that seems to dissipate rather quickly. Perfumy aroma may be a bit much to handle. Overly sweet in the aroma, fairly malty in the flavor department. Lots of citrus and spice. Slides across the palate with a watery mouthfeel, finishes nice and clean despite the low CO2.

Not much in the way of the aroma, but there is a nice lightly hoppy nose. Pours a modest, clear golden color with a textbook frothy head. Flavor is malty as it can be without running the show. Great use of the hops as this beer is neither too bitter nor too tame on the palate. Something happens during the finish that leaves me thirsty for more of this brew whether it be on draught, in a can, or in a bottle. One of my favorite "anytime" lagers.

Ill never trash a beer as long as I live, no matter how nasty is really is. Since St. Ides is not a beer, I would like to take this opportunity to completely annihilate the rating of "The Crooked I". I dont drink forties that often these days, but I do know a good forty from a bad forty. The aroma varies ony slightly from that of 3-days-stale urine combined with draught swill. The thick, supersweet syrup is difficult to swallow and will instantly give you the bubbleguts. And by bubbleguts I mean diarrhea. I may or may not have gagged more than once while choking down this vile, heavy, disgusting excuse for a forty-ounce. I got a headache with 5oz. to go. Terrible.
beer_name: St. Ides High Gravity Malt Liquor

review_blob: I was able to try this one out at Busch Gardens before they gave it a go at the shelves. Wild blue seems to be more of a wine cooler type beverage as opposed to a traditional beer. The blueberry aroma is extremely faint. The flavor? Sugar sweet and quite acidic. Actually, I tasted more grape than blueberry in this "beer", indicating poor choice of artificial blueberry flavoring. Almost no hops in this drop. "Palate-cleansing finish" indeed, as there is virtually no finish at all. Great for 21 year old girls on their birthday.

I tried this one from a bottle. Very nice nutty aroma. Looks stunning in the glass with its rich amber color and medium-sized white foamy head. Flavor is fairly malty, smooth tasty caramel finish. CO2 level could have been a little higher. I would not partake in too many of these in the heat of our Florida summer, but definitely my favorite with food as it is not too heavy or filling.
Faint aroma of hops and pine, and pours pale gold with little head. Flavor isnt bad, but bitterness isnt up to par with other IPAs. Goes down easy.
UPDATED: MAY 13, 2008

This stout has the aroma of a coffee mill. There is a nitro ball in the can that makes all the difference between trash and treasure here. Beautiful crisp line between khaki and black with a supercreamy head that you couldnt get rid of if you tried. Lots of roasted flavors, espresso and cocoa. Nice dry finish, not too sweet. I have not been lucky enough to find this brew on tap anywhere yet, just the tall nitro cans.

From the bottle, standard deep gold color. Very floral as the label suggests. The hop aroma was terrific, and I picked up licorice and pine on the way down with not a whole lot of bitterness left on the tongue. The head tapered off halfway down the glass. Nice IPA for those who havent had an IPA yet.

Living in Tampa is easier to swallow if you wash it down with this locally brewed lager. Slightly hoppier than most big brand lagers with a nice copper color. If Im putting down more than say, a sixpack, it tends to get a little sweet for my taste. If you live on the east coast and youve had your share of this old gem, youd probably agree that its best from the tap or the can. The light green glass consistenly does a great job skunking 2 bottles of every sixpack Ive purchased. If its available, Ill take a Yuengling over a Bud/Coors/Miller lager.
UPDATED: APR 20, 2008
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout
